The 2000s also saw Raaja Sir overdoing the synthesisers which became too jarring sometimes.
I feel Raaja Sir associates an instrument with a scale. The first interlude features some gorgeous  Harmonium phrases.

:40 Raaja Sir is unparalleled when it comes to expanding the boundaries of folk music!
Not in my wildest dreams, I imagined a folk song with a simple 2/4 (subtly swifts to 4/4 in the interludes) pedestrian rhythm laced with flamenco styled guitar riffs and ostinato in bass guitar (just two notes throughout). 
Also a Raaja Sir song without any strings heavy interludes.
I still wonder what prompted Raaja Sir to envisage a bluegrass garnish to our local folk delicacy.
https://youtu.be/0eDX_xoaCyg

This is one of the earliest compositions which slightly deviates from the traditional Pallavi, Charanam structure - that unexpected chorus section after the second interlude!
